        title: "H.H. Holmes",
        year: 1893,
        yearLabel: "1893–1894",
        description:
          "Herman Webster Mudgett — better known by his alias Dr. Henry Howard Holmes, or simply H.H. Holmes — is widely regarded as America's first documented serial killer, and his story reads like a Gothic horror novel set against the gleaming backdrop of the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago.\n\nBorn in 1861 in Gilmanton, New Hampshire, Mudgett displayed signs of intelligence and cruelty from an early age. He enrolled at the University of Michigan Medical School, where he began his criminal career by stealing cadavers, disfiguring them, and filing fraudulent life insurance claims by planting the bodies and claiming they were people who had died accidentally. This macabre scheme provided the seed money for his later enterprises.\n\nArriving in Chicago during the economic boom surrounding the World's Fair, Holmes constructed what would become known as the 'Murder Castle' — a sprawling three-story building at 63rd and Wallace Streets in the Englewood neighborhood. Outwardly a hotel and retail building, the structure was designed as an elaborate death trap. Holmes personally oversaw construction, frequently changing builders so that no one worker understood the building's full layout. The castle contained soundproof rooms, gas lines that Holmes could control from his office, a vault that could be sealed airtight, secret passages, trapdoors, and a basement equipped with a surgical table, vats of acid, a crematorium, and quicklime pits for disposing of remains.\n\nDuring the World's Fair of 1893, which drew 27 million visitors to Chicago, Holmes lured guests — particularly young women — to his hotel. The exact number of his victims will never be known. He confessed to 27 murders, though only 9 could be confirmed, and some researchers believe the true number may be significantly higher. His victims included employees, lovers, and guests, many of whom were never reported missing in the transient chaos of the Fair.\n\nHolmes was ultimately caught not through the murder investigation but through an insurance fraud scheme gone wrong involving his associate Benjamin Pitezel. Holmes had planned to fake Pitezel's death for a $10,000 life insurance payout, but instead actually murdered Pitezel and later killed three of Pitezel's five children as he traveled across the country trying to stay ahead of Pinkerton detectives.\n\nHe was tried, convicted, and hanged on May 7, 1896, at Moyamensing Prison in Philadelphia. According to legend, he requested that his coffin be encased in concrete to prevent his body from being stolen for dissection — an ironic concern given his own history.\n\nThe Holmes case became the subject of Erik Larson's bestselling 2003 book 'The Devil in the White City,' which juxtaposed Holmes's murders with the architectural triumph of the World's Fair, and was adapted into a Hulu series. Holmes remains a figure of dark fascination — a reminder that the most dangerous predators can hide behind charm, intelligence, and the veneer of respectability.",
