        id: "sk-albert-fish",
        title: "Albert Fish ('The Gray Man')",
        year: 1928,
        yearLabel: "1924–1932",
        description:
          "Albert Fish was an American serial killer whose crimes were so depraved that he remains one of the most disturbing figures in the annals of criminal history. Known by numerous aliases — 'The Gray Man,' 'The Werewolf of Wysteria,' 'The Brooklyn Vampire,' and 'The Moon Maniac' — Fish preyed on children during the 1920s and 1930s in a killing spree that shocked even hardened investigators.\n\nBorn Hamilton Howard Fish in Washington, D.C., in 1870, he endured a childhood marked by abandonment and institutional abuse. Placed in an orphanage at age five after his father's death, Fish was subjected to severe beatings and soon developed a disturbing association between pain and pleasure. By his own later admission, he had molested more than 100 children over a span of decades, though the true number may never be known.\n\nFish's most infamous crime was the 1928 murder of 10-year-old Grace Budd. Posing as a kindly elderly man named Frank Howard, Fish visited the Budd family in Manhattan under the pretense of offering employment to Grace's older brother. Instead, he persuaded the family to let him take Grace to a children's party. He took the child to an abandoned cottage in Westchester County, where he murdered her. The details of the crime, which Fish later described in graphic detail, are among the most horrifying in criminal records.\n\nFor six years, the case went unsolved. Then, in 1934, Fish sent an anonymous letter to Grace Budd's mother describing the murder in explicit detail. Investigators traced the letter's distinctive stationery to a rooming house, where they arrested Fish. At the time of his arrest, he was 65 years old — a frail, grandfatherly figure whose appearance gave no hint of the horrors he had committed.\n\nDuring his trial, Fish confessed to three murders — Grace Budd, 4-year-old Billy Gaffney, and 8-year-old Francis McDonnell — though he boasted of additional killings. X-rays taken during his examination revealed 29 needles lodged in his pelvic region, which he had inserted into himself over the years as part of his masochistic practices.\n\nFish's defense argued insanity, and indeed his psychiatric profile was extraordinary — he exhibited virtually every known paraphilia catalogued at the time. However, the jury found him sane and guilty. He was executed in the electric chair at Sing Sing Prison on January 16, 1936.\n\nThe Fish case had lasting implications for child safety awareness in America and contributed to growing public understanding that predators could hide behind the most innocuous appearances. His case also provided early material for the developing field of criminal psychology and remains a benchmark case study in the study of serial predators.",
