        year: 1944,
        yearLabel: "1942–1944",
        description:
          "Marcel Petiot was a French physician who exploited the desperation of Jews and others fleeing Nazi-occupied Paris during World War II, transforming himself into one of the most calculating serial killers in French history. His crimes represent a uniquely horrifying intersection of wartime chaos and psychopathic opportunism.\n\nBorn in Auxerre in 1897, Petiot displayed troubling behavior from childhood, including alleged arson and theft. Despite these warning signs, he earned a medical degree (partly accelerated due to his service in World War I, during which he was wounded and gassed), established a practice in Villeneuve-sur-Yonne, and was even elected mayor. His political career ended amid accusations of drug dealing and the mysterious disappearance of his housekeeper, but he was never charged.\n\nMoving to Paris, Petiot established a practice at 66 Rue Caumartin and cultivated a reputation as a skilled physician. When Germany occupied France in 1940, Petiot saw opportunity in the chaos. He created a fictitious escape network, claiming he could smuggle people out of occupied France to Argentina via a safe route. He charged enormous fees — the equivalent of tens of thousands of dollars — and targeted wealthy Jews, Resistance fighters, and others desperate to flee.\n\nVictims would arrive at Petiot's property at 21 Rue Le Sueur with their valuables and luggage, believing they were about to begin their journey to freedom. Instead, Petiot injected them with what he claimed was a required vaccination but was in fact cyanide. He then stole their possessions and disposed of their bodies in a specially constructed triangular room equipped with a fake door, viewing hole, and lime pit.\n\nPetiot's crimes came to light on March 11, 1944, when neighbors complained about foul-smelling black smoke pouring from the chimney of 21 Rue Le Sueur. Firefighters and police discovered a roaring coal stove in the basement surrounded by dismembered human remains — a scene of unimaginable horror. The remains of at least 26 people were found on the property.\n\nPetiot initially evaded capture by claiming to be a Resistance fighter who had killed German collaborators. He disappeared into the chaos of Liberation-era Paris, even briefly joining the Free French Forces under a false identity. He was finally captured in October 1944.\n\nAt his sensational trial in 1946, Petiot maintained his Resistance cover story with theatrical flair, alternately charming and mocking the court. The jury was unconvinced. He was convicted of 26 counts of murder and sentenced to death. He was guillotined on May 25, 1946, reportedly walking to the blade with a calm demeanor.\n\nThe Petiot case remains a chilling reminder of how wartime conditions create opportunities for predators, and how the desperation of victims can be weaponized against them.",
