        title: "Ed Gein ('The Butcher of Plainfield')",
        year: 1957,
        yearLabel: "1954–1957",
        description:
          "Ed Gein's crimes — discovered in the small town of Plainfield, Wisconsin, in November 1957 — were so shocking and so bizarre that they fundamentally altered American popular culture, inspiring some of the most iconic horror characters in film and literature.\n\nBorn in 1906, Edward Theodore Gein grew up under the domineering influence of his fanatically religious mother, Augusta, who preached that all women (except herself) were instruments of the devil and that the outside world was filled with sin. His father was an alcoholic whom Augusta openly despised. Ed and his brother Henry were kept largely isolated from other children. When Henry died in 1944 under suspicious circumstances (officially ruled accidental, though arson was involved), Ed was left alone with Augusta. Her death in 1945 devastated him.\n\nLeft alone on the family farm, Gein descended into a world of obsessive fantasy. He sealed off his mother's rooms as a shrine and began making nocturnal trips to local cemeteries, where he exhumed recently buried female corpses. He brought the bodies home and used their skin and body parts to create a grotesque collection: a suit made of female skin that he wore around the house, masks made from faces, bowls made from skulls, lampshades made from facial skin, chair seats upholstered with human skin, and numerous other items.\n\nGein's crimes escalated from grave-robbing to murder. He killed at least two women — tavern owner Mary Hogan in 1954 and hardware store owner Bernice Worden in 1957. When police came to the Gein farm investigating Worden's disappearance, they found her decapitated body hanging from the rafters of his shed, dressed out like a deer. The subsequent search of the farmhouse revealed the full extent of his activities.\n\nGein was found legally insane and spent the rest of his life in mental institutions, first at Central State Hospital for the Criminally Insane and later at Mendota Mental Health Institute. He died of cancer in 1984 at age 77.\n\nThe cultural impact of Ed Gein's crimes cannot be overstated. Robert Bloch's novel 'Psycho' (1959), adapted into Alfred Hitchcock's legendary 1960 film, drew direct inspiration from Gein for the character of Norman Bates. Tobe Hooper's 'The Texas Chain Saw Massacre' (1974) borrowed elements of Gein's skin-wearing and rural isolation. Thomas Harris used Gein as partial inspiration for the character of Buffalo Bill in 'The Silence of the Lambs' (1988).\n\nGein's case also contributed significantly to the development of criminal psychology. His extreme maternal attachment, isolation, and the progression from fantasy to grave-robbing to murder provided a case study that informed later understanding of the psychology of serial offenders and the role of childhood environment in shaping violent behavior.",
