        description:
          "Between June 1962 and January 1964, the city of Boston was gripped by terror as thirteen women were sexually assaulted and strangled in their own homes. The killer — dubbed 'The Boston Strangler' by the press — left his victims in deliberately degrading poses, often with stockings or other ligatures tied in decorative bows around their necks.\n\nThe victims ranged in age from 19 to 85 and crossed racial and socioeconomic lines, though the earlier victims were predominantly older women living alone. The apparent randomness of the attacks, combined with the lack of forced entry at most crime scenes (suggesting the victims had voluntarily admitted their killer), created an atmosphere of paranoia that fundamentally changed how Boston's residents — particularly women living alone — went about their daily lives.\n\nThe investigation was one of the largest in Massachusetts history, involving multiple law enforcement agencies, thousands of interviews, and early attempts at psychological profiling. Despite these efforts, the police made no arrest during the killing spree itself.\n\nIn 1965, Albert DeSalvo — a working-class man already in custody for a series of sexual assaults known as the 'Green Man' cases — confessed to being the Boston Strangler. He provided detailed descriptions of the crimes and the victims' apartments that appeared to demonstrate insider knowledge. However, DeSalvo was never tried for the murders. He was instead convicted of the 'Green Man' sexual assaults and sentenced to life in prison.\n\nDeSalvo was stabbed to death in his cell at Walpole State Prison in 1973. His murder was never solved, fueling speculation that he was silenced to protect others involved in the stranglings.\n\nThe case has remained controversial for decades. Many investigators and researchers have questioned whether DeSalvo was truly the Strangler, pointing to inconsistencies in his confessions and the possibility that multiple killers were responsible. In 2013, DNA evidence from the final victim, Mary Sullivan, was linked to DeSalvo through familial DNA testing, and subsequent exhumation and testing of DeSalvo's remains confirmed a match — establishing a definitive connection to at least one of the murders.\n\nWhether DeSalvo committed all thirteen murders, or whether some were the work of different killers whose crimes were grouped together by an investigation desperate for a single suspect, remains a subject of scholarly debate.",
