        yearLabel: "1968–1969",
        description:
          "The Zodiac Killer terrorized the San Francisco Bay Area in the late 1960s and early 1970s, committing at least five confirmed murders and two attempted murders in a spree that generated one of the most famous unsolved cases in American criminal history.\n\nThe confirmed attacks began on December 20, 1968, when two teenagers — David Faraday and Betty Lou Jensen — were shot and killed on a lovers' lane near Vallejo, California. Six months later, on July 4, 1969, the Zodiac shot another couple — Darlene Ferrin and Michael Mageau — at Blue Rock Springs Park, also in Vallejo. Ferrin died; Mageau survived and provided a partial description of the attacker. On September 27, 1969, the killer attacked Bryan Hartnell and Cecelia Shepard at Lake Berryessa, wearing a hooded executioner-style costume with the Zodiac's crosshair symbol on the chest. Shepard died; Hartnell survived. On October 11, 1969, the Zodiac shot and killed cab driver Paul Stine in San Francisco's Presidio Heights neighborhood.\n\nWhat made the Zodiac case unique was the killer's compulsive communication with the press and police. He sent a series of taunting letters to San Francisco-area newspapers, demanding they be published on the front page and threatening mass violence if they were not. The letters contained four cryptograms (coded messages), which the killer claimed would reveal his identity.\n\nThe first cipher (a 408-symbol message split across three letters) was solved within a week by a schoolteacher and his wife, Donald and Bettye Harden. It contained a rambling message about the killer's enjoyment of murder but did not reveal his identity. The second cipher — a 340-character code known as the Z340 — remained unsolved for 51 years until December 2020, when a team of amateur codebreakers (David Oranchak, Sam Blake, and Jarl Van Eycke) cracked it using specialized software. It revealed another taunting message but, again, no identity.\n\nThe investigation consumed enormous resources from multiple law enforcement agencies. Arthur Leigh Allen was the primary suspect for decades, though he was never charged and DNA evidence was inconclusive. Dozens of other suspects have been proposed by researchers, journalists, and amateur investigators, but no definitive identification has ever been made.\n\nThe Zodiac case remains open. It fundamentally changed how law enforcement handles serial cases involving media communication and cryptographic evidence, and it continues to captivate the public imagination more than five decades after the last confirmed attack.",
