        year: 1972,
        yearLabel: "1972–1978",
        description:
          "John Wayne Gacy is one of the most notorious serial killers in American history — a seemingly respectable businessman, community volunteer, and children's entertainer who sexually assaulted, tortured, and murdered at least 33 teenage boys and young men between 1972 and 1978 in the Chicago suburbs.\n\nBorn in 1942 in Chicago, Gacy endured a difficult childhood with an abusive, alcoholic father. Despite this, he became a seemingly successful adult — managing several KFC restaurants, running his own construction business (PDM Contractors), and becoming active in local Democratic politics and community organizations. He was known in his neighborhood for hosting elaborate block parties and entertaining children at hospitals and charity events as 'Pogo the Clown' or 'Patches the Clown.'\n\nBeneath this veneer of civic respectability, Gacy was a predator. He lured victims — typically teenage boys and young men seeking employment — to his home at 8213 West Summerdale Avenue in Norwood Park Township. There he would overpower them using a 'rope trick' (a garrote disguised as a magic trick), sexually assault them, and strangle them. He buried 26 of his victims in the crawl space beneath his house, disposed of three others on his property, and dumped at least four in the Des Plaines River.\n\nGacy came under suspicion in December 1978 after the disappearance of 15-year-old Robert Piest, who was last seen leaving a pharmacy where Gacy had been discussing a construction job. Surveillance of Gacy led investigators to obtain a search warrant for his home. The discovery of decomposing remains in the crawl space — eventually yielding the bodies of 26 young men — was one of the most horrifying crime scenes in American history.\n\nGacy was convicted of 33 murders in 1980 and sentenced to death. He spent 14 years on death row at Menard Correctional Center, during which time he took up oil painting (his clown self-portraits became notorious collectors' items) and gave numerous interviews. He was executed by lethal injection on May 10, 1994. His reported last words were: 'Kiss my ass.'\n\nSeven of Gacy's victims remained unidentified for decades. Through advances in DNA technology and genetic genealogy, investigators have gradually identified the remaining victims, with the most recent identification occurring in 2021. The case fundamentally changed how law enforcement approached missing persons cases involving young men and exposed how societal assumptions about 'respectability' could blind communities to predators in their midst.",
