        title: "Ted Bundy",
        year: 1974,
        yearLabel: "1974–1978",
        description:
          "Ted Bundy is perhaps the most studied and discussed serial killer in history — a handsome, articulate, and seemingly charming law student who raped and murdered at least 30 young women across seven US states between 1974 and 1978, though the true number of his victims is believed to be significantly higher.\n\nBorn Theodore Robert Cowell in Burlington, Vermont, in 1946, Bundy grew up believing his mother was his sister and his grandparents were his parents — a deception he discovered as a teenager, leaving deep psychological scars. Despite this turbulent background, he was outwardly successful: he worked on political campaigns, volunteered at a suicide crisis hotline, and was accepted to law school.\n\nBundy's known killing spree began in 1974 in Washington State. His method was terrifyingly calculated: he would approach young women in public places — on college campuses, at shopping malls, near beaches — feigning injury (wearing a fake cast or sling) or impersonating authority figures to gain their trust. Once he had lured a victim to a secluded location or his Volkswagen Beetle, he would bludgeon, strangle, and sexually assault them. He was known to return to the sites where he had left bodies to engage in necrophilia.\n\nBundy's crimes eventually spanned from Washington to Utah, Colorado, and Florida. He was first arrested in Utah in August 1975 during a routine traffic stop, which led to his connection to the disappearance of several women. He was extradited to Colorado to stand trial for the murder of Caryn Campbell but escaped custody — twice. His first escape was through a courthouse window; his second, more famous escape involved starving himself to fit through a small opening in the ceiling of his cell.\n\nAfter his second escape, Bundy fled to Tallahassee, Florida, where he committed his most savage attacks. On January 15, 1978, he broke into the Chi Omega sorority house at Florida State University and attacked four women in the space of minutes, killing two — Margaret Bowman and Lisa Levy. Three weeks later, he abducted and murdered 12-year-old Kimberly Leach from a junior high school.\n\nBundy was captured for the last time on February 15, 1978, during a routine traffic stop in Pensacola. His trial, which began in June 1979, was one of the first to be nationally televised. Bundy acted as his own attorney, and the proceedings became a media spectacle. He was convicted and sentenced to death.\n\nDuring his decade on death row, Bundy gave extensive interviews, most famously to FBI profiler Robert Keppel and to evangelical broadcaster James Dobson (in which he blamed pornography for his crimes). On the eve of his execution, he confessed to 30 murders across seven states, though investigators believe the true count is higher — possibly as many as 100.\n\nBundy was executed in Florida's electric chair on January 24, 1989. Crowds gathered outside the prison to celebrate, holding signs that read 'Burn, Bundy, Burn' and setting off fireworks.\n\nThe Bundy case transformed criminal profiling, public understanding of psychopathy, and the way law enforcement agencies cooperated across state lines. His ability to appear normal, even likeable, while committing unspeakable acts became a case study in the banality of evil and permanently shattered the assumption that serial killers are easily identifiable outsiders.",
