        yearLabel: "1974–1991",
        description:
          "Dennis Lynn Rader — the self-styled 'BTK' killer, an acronym for 'Bind, Torture, Kill' — terrorized the Wichita, Kansas area for over three decades, murdering ten people between 1974 and 1991 while living a seemingly exemplary life as a husband, father, church congregation president, and city compliance officer.\n\nRader's first murders occurred on January 15, 1974, when he killed four members of the Otero family — Joseph and Julie Otero and two of their children, Josephine (11) and Joseph Jr. (9) — in their home. He later strangled three more victims in 1977: Kathryn Bright, Shirley Vian, and Nancy Fox. After killing Fox, Rader called police to report the murder, beginning a pattern of taunting communications that would define the case.\n\nOver the following years, Rader sent letters, poems, and packages to police and media outlets, describing his crimes in detail and craving public attention. He coined his own moniker, 'BTK,' and included word puzzles and cryptic messages. He killed three more victims in the 1980s and 1991 — Marine Hedge, Vicki Wegerle, and Dolores Davis — before apparently going dormant.\n\nFor 25 years, the BTK case went cold. Then, in 2004, Rader resumed sending communications to the media, apparently frustrated that a book about the case had not given him sufficient credit. In one fateful package, he asked police whether they could trace a floppy disk. They assured him (falsely) that they could not. When Rader sent a floppy disk, forensic analysis recovered metadata showing the disk had last been modified by a user named 'Dennis' at a computer belonging to Christ Lutheran Church in Wichita.\n\nRader was arrested on February 25, 2005. At his sentencing hearing, he calmly and methodically described each of his ten murders in chillingly detached detail, speaking of his victims as 'projects.' He received ten consecutive life sentences — 175 years minimum — with no possibility of parole.\n\nThe BTK case became a landmark study in criminal psychology. Rader's ability to compartmentalize his double life — devoted family man by day, methodical killer by night — challenged assumptions about serial killers and demonstrated how deeply a predator could embed himself in the fabric of ordinary community life. His case also demonstrated how technological ignorance could lead to a killer's downfall, and how the narcissistic need for recognition is often a serial killer's greatest vulnerability.",
        category: "serial-killer",
        era: "serial-killers-golden-age",
        imageUrl: "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/Dennis_Rader_2005_mugshot.jpg/440px-Dennis_Rader_2005_mugshot.jpg",
        sourceLinks: [
          { label: "Wikipedia", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dennis_Rader" },
        ],
