        id: "sk-golden-state-killer",
        title: "Golden State Killer (Joseph James DeAngelo)",
        year: 1974,
        yearLabel: "1974–1986 (caught 2018)",
        description:
          "The Golden State Killer case — finally solved in 2018 after more than four decades — is one of the most significant criminal investigations in American history, both for the scale and depravity of the crimes and for the revolutionary forensic technique that ultimately identified the perpetrator.\n\nJoseph James DeAngelo Jr. was born in 1945 in Bath, New York, and grew up in a military family that moved frequently. He served in the Navy during the Vietnam War and later attended Sacramento State University, earning a degree in criminal justice. He became a police officer — first in Exeter, California, and then in Auburn, California — even as he was simultaneously committing a staggering series of crimes.\n\nDeAngelo's criminal career spanned over a decade and evolved through distinct phases. Between 1974 and 1975, operating in the Visalia area as the 'Visalia Ransacker,' he committed over 100 burglaries and one murder. From 1976 to 1979, as the 'East Area Rapist,' he committed at least 50 sexual assaults in the Sacramento area, breaking into homes at night, binding couples, and raping the women while the men were forced to lie helpless nearby. From 1979 to 1986, as the 'Original Night Stalker,' he committed at least 10 murders in Southern California, targeting couples in their homes.\n\nThe investigation consumed decades and involved multiple law enforcement agencies across California. The various crime series were not linked to a single perpetrator until DNA evidence connected the East Area Rapist to the Original Night Stalker in 2001. Crime writer Michelle McNamara (wife of comedian Patton Oswalt) popularized the name 'Golden State Killer' in a 2013 Los Angeles Magazine article and wrote a bestselling book about the case, 'I'll Be Gone in the Dark,' published posthumously in 2018 after McNamara's death in 2016.\n\nThe breakthrough came through investigative genetic genealogy — a technique pioneered in this case. Investigators uploaded crime scene DNA to GEDmatch, a public genetic genealogy database, and identified distant relatives of the perpetrator. Through painstaking genealogical research, they narrowed the pool of suspects to DeAngelo. Confirmation DNA was obtained surreptitiously from items DeAngelo discarded in public.\n\nDeAngelo was arrested on April 24, 2018, at his home in Citrus Heights, California — a quiet suburban neighborhood where he had lived for decades as a seemingly ordinary retired grandfather. He was 72 years old.\n\nIn June 2020, DeAngelo pleaded guilty to 13 counts of first-degree murder and 13 counts of kidnapping (the statute of limitations had expired on the sexual assaults). He received 26 consecutive life sentences without the possibility of parole. At his sentencing, he briefly broke his silence to say: 'I've listened to all your statements, each one of them. And I'm truly sorry to everyone I've hurt.'\n\nThe Golden State Killer case revolutionized criminal investigation worldwide. The genetic genealogy technique used to identify DeAngelo has since been used to solve hundreds of cold cases across the United States and internationally, fundamentally transforming the relationship between forensic science, genealogy, and criminal justice.",
        category: "serial-killer",
        era: "serial-killers-modern",
        imageUrl: "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Joseph_James_DeAngelo_Sacramento_County_Sheriff.jpg/440px-Joseph_James_DeAngelo_Sacramento_County_Sheriff.jpg",
        sourceLinks: [
          { label: "Wikipedia", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_State_Killer" },
          { label: "FBI", url: "https://www.fbi.gov/history/famous-cases/the-original-night-stalker" },
        ],
