        id: "sk-robert-pickton",
        title: "Robert Pickton",
        year: 1983,
        yearLabel: "1983–2002",
        description:
          "Robert William Pickton — a Canadian pig farmer from Port Coquitlam, British Columbia — was convicted of the second-degree murder of six women and charged with the murders of an additional twenty, making his case one of the largest serial murder investigations in Canadian history. The case exposed devastating systemic failures in how Canadian law enforcement and society treated marginalized women.\n\nBorn in 1949, Pickton grew up on his family's pig farm in Port Coquitlam, east of Vancouver. He and his brother David ran the farm together and hosted large, raucous parties at the property — events that attracted hundreds of people, including bikers, drug dealers, and sex workers from Vancouver's Downtown Eastside.\n\nVancouver's Downtown Eastside is one of Canada's most impoverished urban neighborhoods, with high rates of drug addiction, homelessness, and sex work. Beginning in the late 1980s, women began disappearing from the area at an alarming rate. Families and community organizations reported the disappearances to police, but their concerns were largely dismissed. Many of the missing women were indigenous, and their cases received minimal police attention or media coverage.\n\nPickton first came to police attention in 1997 when a woman he had attacked escaped and reported him. She had been stabbed and handcuffed at the farm. Charges were filed but later stayed when prosecutors concluded the woman's drug use would undermine her credibility as a witness — a decision that allowed Pickton to continue killing for five more years.\n\nPickton was finally arrested in February 2002 after police executed a search warrant at the farm on an unrelated firearms charge. The subsequent investigation of the farm — which became the largest crime scene in Canadian history — lasted years and cost over $100 million. Investigators sifted through tons of soil, farm buildings, and animal pens. Human remains and DNA from 33 women were found on the property. Some remains had been fed through a wood chipper and mixed with pig feed; others were found in freezers alongside pork products.\n\nPickton was charged with 27 counts of first-degree murder but was tried on only six (the Crown decided to proceed with six counts first and hold the remaining charges in reserve). In December 2007, he was convicted of six counts of second-degree murder and sentenced to life in prison with no possibility of parole for 25 years — the maximum sentence available.\n\nThe remaining 20 murder charges were stayed in 2010, a decision that devastated the victims' families. The Missing Women Commission of Inquiry, led by Wally Oppal, concluded in 2012 that police failures were 'blatant' and that the investigation had been hampered by institutional bias against the victims.\n\nRobert Pickton was killed in prison on May 31, 2024, after being attacked by another inmate. He was 74 years old.\n\nThe Pickton case became a watershed moment in Canadian consciousness about violence against indigenous women and the systemic devaluation of marginalized lives. It contributed directly to the establishment of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls (MMIWG), which reported in 2019 that the violence constituted a 'Canadian genocide.'",
        category: "serial-killer",
        era: "serial-killers-modern",
