        id: "sk-samuel-little",
        title: "Samuel Little (Most Prolific US Serial Killer)",
        year: 1970,
        yearLabel: "1970–2005",
        description:
          "In 2018, the Federal Bureau of Investigation officially confirmed Samuel Little as the most prolific serial killer in United States history, with confessions to 93 murders — 60 of which have been verified by law enforcement. His case is a devastating indictment of how systemic racism and the devaluation of marginalized lives allowed a serial predator to operate virtually unchecked for over three decades.\n\nBorn Samuel McDowell in Reynolds, Georgia, in 1940, Little was raised by his grandmother in Lorain, Ohio, after being abandoned by his mother. He had a lengthy criminal record spanning decades, with arrests for assault, armed robbery, fraud, shoplifting, and driving under the influence across multiple states. He was a large, powerfully built man — a former amateur boxer — who lived a drifter's existence, moving from city to city across the American South, Midwest, and West.\n\nLittle's victims were overwhelmingly Black women living on the margins of society — sex workers, women with substance abuse problems, women experiencing homelessness. He killed them by strangulation, a method that often leaves little forensic evidence and can be mistaken for drug overdose, accidental death, or natural causes. Many of his victims' deaths were never investigated as homicides.\n\nLittle was first arrested for murder in 2012 based on DNA evidence linking him to three Los Angeles-area killings in the 1980s. He was convicted in 2014 and sentenced to three consecutive life sentences. Initially, investigators believed these were his only murders.\n\nThe breakthrough came in 2018, when Texas Ranger James Holland conducted an extraordinary series of interrogations with Little at a Texas prison. Holland's approach was patient and relationship-based — he spent hundreds of hours with Little over many months, building rapport and encouraging Little to share his memories. Little began confessing to murder after murder, providing detailed descriptions of victims, locations, and methods.\n\nLittle confessed to 93 murders committed between 1970 and 2005 across 19 states. He demonstrated an extraordinary visual memory, providing detailed drawings of his victims' faces — sketches that were published by the FBI in hopes of identifying still-unknown victims. As of the latest count, 60 of his confessions have been matched to confirmed cases.\n\nLittle died in prison on December 30, 2020, at age 80. Many of his victims remain unidentified.\n\nThe Samuel Little case forced a national reckoning with the concept of 'less dead' victims — a term coined by criminologists to describe individuals whose murders receive less attention from law enforcement and media because of their race, socioeconomic status, or lifestyle. His decades-long killing spree was possible precisely because his victims' lives and deaths were systematically undervalued by the institutions that should have protected them.",
        category: "serial-killer",
