        id: "sk-lonnie-david-franklin",
        title: "Lonnie David Franklin Jr. ('The Grim Sleeper')",
        year: 1985,
        yearLabel: "1985–2007",
        description:
          "The 'Grim Sleeper' — Lonnie David Franklin Jr. — murdered at least ten women and one man in South Los Angeles over a span of more than twenty years, with an apparent 14-year gap in killings between 1988 and 2002 that gave him his chilling nickname. His case is both a landmark in forensic genealogy and a searing indictment of how race and geography determined which victims received justice.\n\nFranklin was born in 1952 in South Los Angeles. He worked as a garage attendant for the Los Angeles Police Department and as a trash collector for the city — a job that gave him intimate knowledge of the neighborhoods where he hunted. He was a married father who lived in a quiet residential street, and his neighbors described him as friendly and ordinary.\n\nFranklin's known victims were all Black women and girls from South Los Angeles, aged 15 to 35. Most were involved in sex work or had substance abuse problems. He shot or strangled them and dumped their bodies in alleys, dumpsters, and vacant lots in the neighborhoods where they had lived. The first known murder occurred in 1985; the last confirmed killing was in 2007.\n\nThe 14-year apparent gap between 1988 and 2002 — which gave the killer his 'Grim Sleeper' moniker — may not have been a true dormancy. Investigators believe Franklin may have continued killing during this period but that the victims simply were not connected to his case. In South Los Angeles during the crack epidemic, the deaths of marginalized women were frequently attributed to drug overdoses or gang violence without thorough investigation.\n\nThe case gained wider attention in 2008 when LA Weekly journalist Christine Pelisek published a detailed investigation revealing the pattern of unsolved murders. Community activists, particularly members of the Black Coalition Fighting Back Serial Murders, had been calling attention to the killings for years but had been largely ignored by mainstream media and law enforcement leadership.\n\nFranklin was identified in 2010 through familial DNA searching — a technique in which DNA from a crime scene is compared to profiles in California's criminal DNA database to identify relatives of the perpetrator. A partial match to Franklin's son led investigators to Franklin himself. An undercover officer posed as a waiter at a pizza restaurant Franklin frequented and collected utensils and napkins he had used. The DNA from these items matched crime scene evidence.\n\nFranklin was arrested on July 7, 2010. He was convicted of ten counts of murder and one count of attempted murder in 2016 and sentenced to death. He died in prison on March 28, 2020, at age 67, before the sentence could be carried out.\n\nThe Grim Sleeper case became a powerful symbol of the 'missing white woman syndrome' — the documented pattern in which the disappearances and murders of white women receive vastly more media coverage and investigative resources than those of women of color. The case contributed to reforms in how the LAPD handles serial crime investigations in marginalized communities.",
        category: "serial-killer",
        era: "serial-killers-modern",
        sourceLinks: [
          { label: "Wikipedia", url: "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grim_Sleeper" },
        ],
